{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651495"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.9,0,0.05,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76272"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11189"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61779"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76272"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner requesting a screening mammogram. She has no family history of breast cancer and no symptoms. Current guidelines do not recommend routine mammographic screening in her age group due to high false positive rates and unnecessary interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario illustrates the application of key ethical principles in healthcare decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the principle of beneficence in medical ethics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acting to promote patient wellbeing","Allowing patients complete freedom of choice","Distributing healthcare resources equally","Maintaining patient confidentiality","Obtaining informed consent"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe principle of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacting to promote patient wellbeing\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes beneficence in medical ethics. This principle creates a moral obligation for healthcare providers to take positive actions that benefit patients and protect them from harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintaining patient confidentiality\u003C/strong\u003E relates to the principle of non-maleficence and respect for privacy, which is distinct from actively promoting patient wellbeing.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistributing healthcare resources equally\u003C/strong\u003E describes the principle of justice, which focuses on fair allocation of healthcare resources across society.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllowing patients complete freedom of choice\u003C/strong\u003E describes patient autonomy, which is a separate ethical principle that must be balanced against beneficence.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObtaining informed consent\u003C/strong\u003E primarily relates to respecting patient autonomy and ensuring patients can make informed decisions about their care.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile beneficence is fundamental to medical practice, it must be balanced against other ethical principles, particularly patient autonomy. Healthcare providers must consider what constitutes benefit from both medical and patient perspectives.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beneficence is the ethical principle that requires healthcare providers to act in the best interest of their patients.","The principle of beneficence creates a positive obligation to promote patient wellbeing and prevent harm.","Beneficence must be balanced against patient autonomy and other ethical principles in medical decision-making."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61779"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61779"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T17:37:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T17:37:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11189"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76272"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","